               <msContents class="#STM">
                  <summary>
                    <p>This manuscript is part of an assortment of three fragments found with Sanscrit 1347. This fragment contains, on the recto side, a <title xml:lang="sa">Bhuvaneśvarīkavaca</title>, a hymn for protection addressed to the goddess <term xml:lang="sa">Bhuvaneśvarī</term>, in <term xml:lang="sa">anuṣṭubh</term> meter.  The verso side is perhaps a different <term xml:lang="sa">kavaca</term> hymn, also in <term xml:lang="sa">anuṣṭubh</term> meter. The small size of the manuscript suggests that it may have been used as an amulet or charm.</p>
                    <p>On line 3, <locus facs="4">1r</locus>, the text seems to contain the unusual word <term xml:lang="sa">suḍaṅga</term>, which may be a mistake for <term xml:lang="sa">ṣaḍaṅga</term>. However, <term xml:lang="sa">suḍaṅga</term> appears in the <title xml:lang="sa">Śabdakalpadruma</title> lexicon, under the entry for <term xml:lang="sa">gūḍhamārgaḥ</term>: <q xml:lang="sa">suḍaṅga iti bhāṣā</q> (1821, <ref target="https://www.digitale-sammlungen.de/en/view/bsb10219712?page=804">802</ref>).</p>
               </summary>
